		The labmc software
		
For the analysis of experimental rock deformation data.
Created by Jun Korenaga, Yale University, in 2008.
Modified in 2015 by Benjamin G. Mullet (Mullet et al., 2015).
Further optimized in 2019 by Chhavi Jain (Jain et al., 2019).

The labmc software is designed to perform nonlinear inversion of experimental
data on the plastic deformation of mineral assemblages. It is based on a
Markov chain Monte Carlo sampling technique.
The software allows users to fit experimentally observed strain rates with a
composite rheological model, i.e., a combination of different creep mechanisms,
which is often a more realistic and physically meaningfulrheological model to
explain the observed deformation than the assumption of a single creep mechanism.

The tutorial explains the method for the installation and implementation of
the software. Nine worked-out examples are provided (Cases S1-S9) with the
requisite scripts to demonstrate the implementation of the code. MATLAB scripts
are also provided to process the MCMC output.
Refer to the following publications to understand the MCMC inversion
scheme implemented by the labmc software:

Korenaga, J. and Karato, S.I., 2008. A new analysis of experimental data on
olivine rheology. Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid Earth, 113(B2).

Mullet, B.G., Korenaga, J. and Karato, S.I., 2015. Markov chain Monte Carlo
inversion for the rheology of olivine single crystals. Journal of Geophysical
Research: Solid Earth, 120(5), pp.3142-3172.

Jain, C., Korenaga, J. and Karato, S.I., 2019. Global analysis of experimental
data on the rheology of olivine aggregates. Journal of Geophysical Research:
Solid Earth, 124(1), pp.310-334.

Jain, C. and Korenaga, J. An open-source Markov chain Monte Carlo inversion
software for the analysis of experimental rock deformation data (in prep., March 2026).
